The surface chemistry of these materials was also analyzed by XPS. The XPS spectrum of BNCDs confirmed the boron and nitrogen functionalization of CDs [43]. Here, the presence of four distinct peaks at 192.08, 408, 284.08, and 532 eV was ascribed to boron (B1s), nitrogen (N1s), carbon (C1s), and oxygen (O1s), respectively (Fig. 5
                        a). Here, the deconvoluted high resolution-XPS (HR-XPS) spectrum of C1s showed three peaks at 288.64 (O-CO), 286.4 (CO), and 284.73 eV (CC/CH) (Fig. 5b). Fig. 5(c) shows the HR-XPS spectrum for N1s with distinct peaks at 401.52 eV (1°/2° amino) and 400.17 eV (pyrrolic B-Ns). In the case of B1s (Fig. 5d), three peaks at 191.056, 193.01 and 192.42 eV confirmed the occurrence of B-N, B-O, and B-CO2, respectively. In the case of Tb-MOF (Fig. 6
                        ), the XPS peaks of different elements (O, N, and C) were found at 531.28, 399.38, and 284.08 eV, respectively. The peaks at 1242, 1276, and 151 eV confirmed the 3d (3d5/2, 3d3/2) and 4d oxidation states of Tb. In the case of BNCDs/Tb-MOF, there is a slight shift in the XPS peak positions of pristine Tb-MOF (Fig. 7
                        ) [44]. The deconvolution of the C1s orbital at binding energies of 288.74 eV can be assigned to the CO group present in the carboxylate group of H3BTC linkers. In contrast, B1s at 192.84 eV confirmed the presence of B-C bonds due to the BN-carbon dot in BNCD/Tb-MOF. These results confirmed the existence of a strong interaction between BNCDs and Tb-MOF in BNCDs@Tb-MOF composites.
